Located in Honesdale, Pennsylvania, Fox Hill Farm is a small farm with a big vision. item.title: Weddings
item.dc:creator: foxhillfarm
item.content:encoded:
“You’d like to get married here? On the farm?!”

And just like that, barn weddings at Fox Hill Farm began! Three years and many celebrations later, we continue to dedicate ourselves to making each couple’s celebration an elegantly beautiful, memorable and seamless day.

Pond-side outdoor ceremony, cocktail hour in the garden, then dinner and dancing in the 19th century rustic barn make for a fabulous experience throughout the farm on your wedding day here at the farm.  Your creative flair can be added to the treasures found around every corner. These treasures throughout the farm pay homage to the history of farming in northeast Pennsylvania, yet provide a unique atmosphere for you and your guests. The centerpiece of the farm, the barn, still has its original structure. There is a grand entrance, dance floor and  separate catering area, plus a long dining 'hall' which seats approximately 160 people. Last year saw the completion of our bathhouse adjoining the barn. Both men and women can enjoy the comforts of modern day restrooms, complete with decor people love - even in the bathroom!  Once the lights are on, the tables are set, the music is on, and the party commences, the barn seems to emanate comfort and love. Guests are in awe!

Our newly renovated cottage is the perfect place for the bride and her maids to prepare for the big day and it is also available for the newlyweds to stay in while they prepare and/or the night of the wedding. For the groom and groomsmen, also newly renovated and just finished, is the Fox Den! Located in the barn, the den has comfortable leather seating, great lighting and farm treasures used as decor throughout. Clients love these special options for their wedding party. As we only have one wedding per weekend, couples have from Tuesday through Sunday to take their time decorating, preparing and making the celebration their own, then plenty of time to take down the following day. 

Fox Hill Farm, nestled in the Delaware Valley Highlands, just north of the Poconos and west of the New York border, would love to be your unforgettable and unforgettably beautiful venue!

item.title: Flowers
item.dc:creator: foxhillfarm
item.content:encoded:
FARM FRESH LOCALLY AND SUSTAINABLY GROWN FLOWERS

We are obsessed with flowers at Fox Hill Farm and believe their importance on your wedding day is at the top of the list! As you will see by our extensive gardens throughout the property, we cannot get enough of flowers. We responsibly grow and use as much from the farm as possible to create a unique look for your day. Katharine works with couples to create a unique floral look and complete style for weddings not only on the farm, but all over eastern Pennsylvania, New York and beyond.  What we cannot grow, we find; sourcing locally when possible. Experience our obsession with flowers via your wedding!

item.title: About
item.dc:creator: foxhillfarm
item.content:encoded: Born in the late-nineteenth century farmhouse on the property, George always hoped he would come back, raise his own family on the farm and work in the family business. Little did he know, his wife would not only embrace farm life, but truly love it and start digging immediately. George and Katharine realized it was a blank slate for growing flowers, grass fed beef, pastured poultry, and most importantly, children! With tons of help from friends and family near and far, Fox Hill Farm is a beautiful place to come plan and celebrate.

[push h="20"]Working from home meant we could vary snack and coffee breaks, change our desks or view, goof off, drink on the job, even spend the day in pajamas, and often meet to gossip or share ideas. On the other hand, we bossed ourselves around, set impossible goals, and demanded longer hours than office jobs usually entail. It was the ultimate “flextime,” in that it depended on how flexible we felt each day, given deadlines, distractions, and workaholic crescendos. Aristotle made several efforts to explain how moral conduct contributes to the good life for human agents, including the Eqikh EudaimonhV and the Magna Moralia, but the most complete surviving statement of his views on morality occurs in the Eqikh Nikomacoi .[push h="20"]

Successful people ask better questions.

But on Aristotle’s view, the lives of individual human beings are invariably linked together in a social context.
